      <p class="apn-f-section-label">Your Current State</p>
      <h2 class="apn-f-headline">What Your Score Actually Means</h2>
      <div class="apn-f-divider"></div>

      <div id="apn-f-score-context"></div>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        A 90-plus focus score looks like this: the athlete enters a focused state within 5 minutes of beginning the pre-training ritual. Focus quality stays consistent from the first minute to the last. Technique performance does not degrade with session fatigue. Motivation is internally generated, not dependent on stimulants or external hype. Skill acquisition from training translates to competitive performance because the acetylcholine-dependent encoding process is intact.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-f-data-callout">
        <p class="stat">20%</p>
        <p class="stat-desc">The brain's share of total resting energy consumption, despite representing only 2% of body mass. Cognitive performance is an energy problem before it is a motivation problem. When mitochondrial efficiency in neural tissue drops, focus drops first. Physical fatigue follows later. Athletes interpret this as "mind over matter." The mechanism is mitochondrial, not motivational.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tier-conditional framing -->
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="rookie">
        <div class="apn-f-pull-quote">
          <p>"This is the most important single change you will make this month. Without focus, your training is producing half the skill acquisition and technique retention it should. You are putting in the reps. The neural encoding is not keeping up."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-f-body">You are early. That means the gains from closing this gap are immediate and large. A consistent pre-training focus ritual alone will measurably improve skill retention within 2 to 3 weeks.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="competitor">
        <div class="apn-f-pull-quote">
          <p>"One gap is holding back everything else you are building. Your conditioning is improving. Your strength is improving. But technique errors under pressure and focus drop-off in the second half of sessions are capping your ceiling. Close this first."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-f-body">The competitor's problem is usually mid-session focus degradation. The dopaminergic system runs out of substrate before the session ends. The protocol addresses this directly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete">
        <div class="apn-f-pull-quote">
          <p>"You are in the optimization zone. The gap between your physical ceiling and your current output is cognitive. Attention quality, motivation consistency, and skill acquisition rate are the remaining variables. This is where precision produces results."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-f-body">At the Athlete tier, this is a data-driven gap. Session focus quality measured against RPE. Caffeine timing optimized. Mitochondrial support introduced. The protocol is specific.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite">
        <div class="apn-f-pull-quote">
          <p>"At your level, focus is a competitive edge, not a comfort. Every technique error under fatigue, every session where attention fragments in the final 20 minutes: that is a gap your competitors may not have. Close it."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-f-body">Elite-level focus management involves timing precision across the dopaminergic, cholinergic, and adenosinergic systems simultaneously. The protocol is designed for that specificity.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion">
        <div class="apn-f-pull-quote">
          <p>"Protect this. Cognitive performance at peak levels degrades faster than physical performance when the supporting systems are neglected. The architecture that sustains your focus over a full competitive season is what this page is about."</p>
        </div>
        <p class="apn-f-body">At the Champion tier, maintenance and protection are the disciplines. The protocol shifts from building to sustaining. Nothing is assumed. Everything is measured.</p>
      </div>

      <div style="border-top:3px solid #06A5C5;background:#F4F4F2;padding:24px 28px;margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:4px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 10px;">Quick Win: Do This Before Your Next Session</p>
        <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0 0 12px;"><strong>Implement a 5-minute pre-training focus transition before your next session today.</strong></p>
        <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Sit down. Remove all distractions. Set a 5-minute timer. Write three specific performance targets for the session (not general like "work hard." Specific: "Maintain elbow position on all overhead presses" or "Keep heart rate below 160 during round 2"). The act of specifying targets primes the prefrontal cortex for selective attention. The reticular activating system (RAS) filters incoming sensory data toward what you have declared as important. This is a neurological function. You are directing it deliberately rather than letting noise direct it for you.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ====================================================
       MODULE 2: WHY THIS IS COSTING YOU
  ===================================================== -->
  <div id="apn-f-m2" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-f-content">
      <p class="apn-f-section-label">The Science</p>
      <h2 class="apn-f-headline">The Mechanism Behind Your Gap</h2>
      <div class="apn-f-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        Focus, motivation, and cognitive drive are not character traits. They are neurochemical states. The primary systems governing them are the dopaminergic system (motivation and drive), the cholinergic system (working memory and skill acquisition), and the adenosinergic system (mental fatigue accumulation). Understanding which system is most compromised for you is how you target the solution.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin:32px 0 12px;">The Dopaminergic System</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        Dopamine controls motivation, drive, and the anticipation of reward. Dopamine is not released when you achieve something. It is released when you anticipate achieving something. This is the neural mechanism behind "wanting" to train. When dopamine signaling is blunted, training feels like something you should do rather than something you want to do. The training itself does not feel less rewarding. You lose access to the anticipatory drive that gets you there and keeps you focused once you arrive.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        Dopamine depletion happens through chronic overstimulation. If your dopaminergic system is constantly activated by high-dopamine inputs (social media, constant notifications, processed food, habitual caffeine use without adenosine management), the receptor sensitivity downregulates. You need more input to achieve the same drive signal. Training, which produces a moderate dopamine response, feels flat compared to the high-input environment you have adapted to.
      </p>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin:32px 0 12px;">The Adenosinergic System</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        Adenosine is the brain's fatigue signal. It accumulates in neural tissue proportionally to metabolic activity. When adenosine concentration crosses a threshold, you feel mentally fatigued. Caffeine works by binding to adenosine receptors and blocking the signal. It does not produce energy. It prevents the fatigue signal from being received. When the caffeine wears off, the adenosine that accumulated while the receptors were blocked floods the receptors at once. This is the crash. The solution is not more caffeine. It is managing adenosine accumulation through cognitive load distribution and sleep, which is when adenosine clears from neural tissue.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-f-data-callout">
        <p class="stat">47%</p>
        <p class="stat-desc">Percentage of waking hours the average person spends mind-wandering, based on Harvard research using experience-sampling methodology. In athletes, this rate inside training sessions correlates directly with reduced skill acquisition, higher technique error rates under fatigue, and lower session quality ratings. The mind wandering is not random. It is the absence of a deliberate attentional direction protocol.</p>
      </div>

      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin:32px 0 12px;">The Cholinergic System</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        Acetylcholine is the neurotransmitter responsible for working memory, attentional focus, and skill acquisition. During technical training, acetylcholine is released in the cortex to maintain attention on the task. During skill acquisition, acetylcholine facilitates long-term potentiation (LTP) at synaptic junctions, which is the cellular mechanism of skill encoding. If acetylcholine availability is low, technique instructions do not encode as efficiently. You perform the drill. The neural pattern does not consolidate as deeply. The skill acquisition plateaus.
      </p>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        Acetylcholine precursors are dietary. Choline from eggs, beef liver, and seafood is required for acetylcholine synthesis. Athletes with low choline intake have measurably reduced working memory performance and slower skill acquisition rates. DHA, a structural component of synaptic membranes, also supports cholinergic signaling efficiency.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-f-warning">
        <p class="apn-f-warning-label">Common Mistake</p>
        <p>Using caffeine as the primary focus intervention. Caffeine blocks adenosine receptors. It does not increase dopamine synthesis. It does not improve acetylcholine availability. It does not enhance mitochondrial efficiency. Caffeine alone produces stimulation without the attentional quality that characterizes real cognitive performance. The result is a heightened but scattered mental state. Without L-theanine to modulate the GABA-ergic anxiety component, caffeine above 150mg frequently produces an anxious, distracted state rather than clean focus. Caffeine without L-theanine is an incomplete intervention.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Compounding effects -->
      <h3 style="font-family:Georgia,serif;font-size:20px;color:#0D0D0D;margin:32px 0 12px;">How This Degrades Your Other Pillars</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">
        <strong>Training quality:</strong> Focus degradation in the second half of sessions means technique errors accumulate when fatigue is highest. This is when injury risk peaks and when the training stimulus is most specific to competition conditions. Encoding a flawed movement pattern under fatigue is worse than not training that pattern at all.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-f-body">
        <strong>Recovery:</strong> Poor focus during training leads to inefficient motor recruitment, meaning you generate more metabolic waste for the same output. Inefficient movement is harder to recover from. Focus quality directly affects how clean the training stimulus is.
      </p>
      <p class="apn-f-body">
        <strong>Stress management:</strong> The prefrontal cortex, the region responsible for sustained attention, is also the primary regulator of the HPA stress axis. Focus impairment and stress dysregulation are bidirectional. Closing the focus gap reduces the chronic low-level sympathetic activation that comes from mental scatter throughout the day.
      </p>

      <!-- Tier-conditional cost blocks -->
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">At the Rookie tier, unfocused training produces unfocused adaptation. Technique is being encoded with errors because attention drifts during reps. The reps are going in. The correct movement pattern is not being reinforced at the neural level. You are building habits during those reps, and without attention, you may be building the wrong ones.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">At the Competitor tier, focus degradation in the second half of sessions is costing you the most specific training adaptation. The hardest reps, the ones where you are most fatigued, are closest to competition conditions. Those are exactly when your focus breaks. You train 90% of the way to where it matters. The last 10% is where competition lives.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">At the Athlete tier, motivation inconsistency is the primary cost. You have weeks of excellent training followed by weeks where motivation is significantly lower. That is not discipline fluctuation. It is dopaminergic system inconsistency. Your drive is a neurochemical state. This protocol stabilizes it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">At the Elite tier, focus is the competitive margin. Two athletes with identical physical conditioning: the one with better session focus quality acquires skill faster, makes fewer fatigue errors, and executes technique more reliably under pressure. The physical gap narrows at your level. The cognitive gap does not.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:32px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">What This Gap Costs You Right Now</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">At the Champion tier, focus protection is a longevity discipline. Chronic reliance on stimulants without proper adenosine management accelerates receptor downregulation. Years of unchecked caffeine use without cycling and L-theanine pairing will erode the baseline focus quality you have built. Protect the system that sustains your performance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

