  <!-- ====================================================
       MODULE 4: THE PROTOCOL
  ===================================================== -->
  <div id="apn-f-m4" style="background:#F4F4F2;">
    <div class="apn-f-content">
      <p class="apn-f-section-label">The Protocol</p>
      <h2 class="apn-f-headline">Your 30-Day Focus Closure Plan</h2>
      <div class="apn-f-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-f-body">Four weeks. One gap. Here is exactly what to do. The protocol is built from behavioral and neurochemical principles. Each week adds one layer. Do not skip ahead.</p>

      <!-- WEEK 1 -->
      <p class="apn-f-week-header">Week 1</p>
      <h3 class="apn-f-week-title">Establish the Pre-Training Focus Ritual</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">The most impactful change you can make this week costs zero dollars and takes 5 minutes. The pre-training focus ritual is the behavioral anchor for the entire protocol. Without it, every other intervention is less effective because you are not directing your attentional system before the session begins.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>The 5-Step Pre-Training Ritual. Same sequence before every single session this week:</strong></p>

      <p class="apn-f-body" style="padding-left:16px;border-left:3px solid #06A5C5;margin:20px 0;">
        <strong>Step 1 (90 seconds): Transition.</strong> Physical separation from whatever you were doing. Sit. Put the phone face down. Two slow breaths to signal a context switch to the nervous system.<br><br>
        <strong>Step 2 (60 seconds): Session intention.</strong> Name the specific physical and technical focus of this session. Not a goal. A target. "I am working squat depth today" or "I am holding my guard position during round 3."<br><br>
        <strong>Step 3 (60 seconds): Review the last session.</strong> What worked? What needs correction? This activates the working memory retrieval that links today's session to the adaptation from the last one. The brain learns in sequences, not in isolated events.<br><br>
        <strong>Step 4 (60 seconds): Physiological activation.</strong> 20 bodyweight squats or 30 seconds of jumping jacks. This triggers catecholamine release (dopamine, norepinephrine) that primes the prefrontal cortex for sustained attention. Warm-up is not just physical. It is neurochemical.<br><br>
        <strong>Step 5 (30 seconds): Commitment.</strong> Say out loud, or write down: "I am here. I am present. This session matters." This is not affirmation theater. It is a prefrontal cortex activation cue. Speaking an intention creates a stronger neural trace than thinking it.
      </p>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Do the 5-step ritual before every session this week. Every single one. No exceptions. That is your only task this week. Consistency matters more than perfection. Even a 3-minute version is better than skipping it. Lock this habit before adding anything else.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full 5-step ritual before every session. Additionally, rate your focus quality at the end of each session on a 1 to 10 scale. Record it. This is your baseline measurement. You will compare Week 4 against it. The metric is: focus quality, not effort or session difficulty.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full ritual plus post-session logging: focus quality (1 to 10), the session RPE (1 to 10), and the quality of the final 20 minutes specifically (1 to 10). After 7 sessions, look at the correlation between session RPE and final-20-minute focus quality. That correlation tells you where the adenosine and dopamine systems are breaking down.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full ritual plus detailed session log: focus quality, RPE, technique error count (estimate), time into session when focus first degraded. Seven sessions of this data gives you a precise map of your cognitive fatigue curve. That curve is what you are engineering against in Weeks 3 and 4.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 1 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Audit your current pre-training routine. Is it systematic? Is it the same every time? Inconsistency in the pre-training ritual at your level produces inconsistency in session quality. This week, write out your exact sequence and standardize it. Every session starts exactly the same way.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-f-assignment">
        <p class="apn-f-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>By end of Week 1: The 5-step ritual completed before every training session this week. Session focus quality logged every day. Your Week 1 average focus quality score is your baseline number. Write it down.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 2 -->
      <p class="apn-f-week-header" style="margin-top:48px;">Week 2</p>
      <h3 class="apn-f-week-title">Stimulant Audit: Caffeine Timing Optimization</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">Most athletes have a caffeine problem they do not recognize as a problem. Not too much caffeine. Incorrectly timed caffeine. This week, you fix it without necessarily reducing consumption.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 1: No caffeine after 1pm.</strong> Caffeine's half-life is 5 to 6 hours. A coffee at 3pm means half that dose is still in your system at 8 or 9pm. Adenosine clearance during sleep is interrupted because caffeine is still blocking adenosine receptors. You go to sleep with accumulated adenosine that does not fully clear. You wake up with a higher adenosine baseline than yesterday. Your cognitive baseline trends down week over week. This is why athletes who "need more caffeine to feel normal" have often just accumulated adenosine debt across weeks of late-afternoon caffeine use.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 2: Do not consume caffeine within 90 minutes of waking.</strong> Cortisol is at its peak in the first 60 to 90 minutes after waking. This is the cortisol awakening response (CAR). Caffeine taken during this window competes with the CAR for alertness but does not add to it. You blunt the CAR and displace it. The result is an earlier need for the caffeine top-up later in the morning. Waiting 90 minutes lets the CAR complete. Your natural alertness peaks without caffeine. When you add caffeine at 90 minutes, you are layering on top of a full CAR, which produces meaningfully better cognitive output.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 3: Log your current caffeine timing for 7 days.</strong> Write down every caffeinated beverage and when you consumed it. Do not change behavior yet. Observe. The data from this week will show the pattern you are fixing.</p>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">One rule this week: no caffeine after 1pm. That is it. Log your sleep quality this week and compare to Week 1. If your sleep quality improves, the late caffeine was suppressing your adenosine clearance. The correlation will be clear within 3 to 4 days.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">No caffeine after 1pm. Delay first caffeine to 90 minutes after waking. Log morning alertness each day (1 to 10) before caffeine. After 7 days, compare your pre-caffeine morning alertness to Week 1. If it has improved, the CAR protocol is working. Your natural alertness floor is rising.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full caffeine timing audit. No caffeine after 1pm. First caffeine at 90 minutes post-waking. If you currently train in the morning, time your pre-training caffeine (if used) at 30 minutes before the session, not immediately before. Pre-workout stims taken within 15 minutes of training produce a stimulant spike that peaks during the session's second half when you are already fatigued. Timing it earlier blunts the peak-crash curve.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Precision caffeine audit. Total daily caffeine calculated. No late-afternoon use. 90-minute post-waking delay implemented. Consider a 5 to 7 day caffeine tolerance reset at the end of this week (no caffeine, days 7 to 11) if your current tolerance is high. A reset restores adenosine receptor sensitivity. The effect of your standard dose will be significantly stronger after the reset period.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 2 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Validate your current caffeine timing protocol. If it is already optimal, this week confirms it. If there are any late-afternoon exceptions, eliminate them. At the Champion tier, protecting adenosine receptor sensitivity is a season-long discipline. Tolerance creep is the enemy. Periodic 5-day resets quarterly maintain receptor sensitivity without sacrificing daily performance.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-f-assignment">
        <p class="apn-f-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>By end of Week 2: No caffeine after 1pm for 7 days. First caffeine at 90-plus minutes post-waking. Morning alertness baseline logged. Compare to Week 1 baseline. Your caffeine timing pattern is now documented and corrected.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 3 -->
      <p class="apn-f-week-header" style="margin-top:48px;">Week 3</p>
      <h3 class="apn-f-week-title">Introduce the Clarity and Ignite Stack</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">The behavioral foundation is built. The caffeine architecture is optimized. Week 3 introduces the supplement stack from Module 5. The stack works on top of the protocol. Not instead of it.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 1: Clarity drops (Methylene Blue) introduced.</strong> 5 to 10 drops sublingually 30 to 45 minutes before training. The mechanism is mitochondrial: methylene blue acts as an electron carrier in the mitochondrial electron transport chain, accepting electrons from NADH and donating them to cytochrome c. This bypasses Complex I and II dysfunction in compromised mitochondria, restoring ATP production in neural tissue. The result is improved cognitive energy production at the cellular level, specifically addressing the mental fatigue that degrades session quality in the second half. Take it before the session. Not with caffeine simultaneously. Space them by 20 minutes if using both.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 2: Track the response.</strong> Rate your focus quality in the second half of sessions (last 20 to 30 minutes) specifically this week. Compare to your Week 1 baseline for the same metric. Methylene blue's effect on mitochondrial efficiency should be measurable in session focus quality within 5 to 7 sessions of consistent use.</p>

      <!-- Scripture block - mid-protocol -->
      <div class="apn-f-scripture">
        <p>"Whatever you do, work at it with all your heart, as working for the Lord, not for human masters."</p>
        <p>Colossians 3:23</p>
      </div>

      <p class="apn-f-body">The standard in every session is not comparison to another athlete. It is the question of whether you brought everything you were given to bring. Focused, present, deliberate. Not scattered. Not half-in. If the session is worth doing, it is worth the full attention you have been equipped to give. The protocol is how you access that standard consistently.</p>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Start with Clarity drops only this week. 5 drops sublingually before every session. Track your second-half session focus quality daily. One new variable at a time. The ritual is already in place. This is the first supplement layer. Do not add Ignite yet.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Clarity drops introduced (5 to 10 drops sublingually, 30 to 45 minutes before training). Track second-half focus quality. If you currently use a pre-workout stimulant, evaluate whether Ignite from Module 5 can replace it. The caffeine plus L-theanine combination in Ignite will produce cleaner focus than most stimulant-heavy pre-workouts without the anxiety spike.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full stack introduction: Clarity drops plus Ignite. Clarity 30 to 45 minutes pre-training. Ignite 20 to 30 minutes pre-training. The timing sequence matters: Clarity first, then Ignite. Track focus quality first half versus second half separately. You are looking for the second-half gap to close.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full stack with precise timing. Clarity at T-45 minutes. Ignite at T-25 minutes. Session begins at T-0. Log the subjective peak focus window: when in the session is your cognitive performance highest? At the Elite tier, timing the stack to push that peak window into the session's highest-skill or highest-intensity period is the precision target.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 3 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Validate the full stack timing against your current protocol. Make adjustments based on your session data. At this tier, you already have a pre-training protocol. This week is about integrating Clarity drops if they are not already part of it, and confirming the timing optimization for your specific session structure.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-f-assignment">
        <p class="apn-f-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>By end of Week 3: Clarity drops used before every training session. Second-half session focus quality logged and compared to Week 1 baseline. First-half vs. second-half focus quality gap measured. You should see that gap narrowing. If it is not, the timing or dose needs adjustment (see Module 5).</p>
      </div>

      <!-- WEEK 4 -->
      <p class="apn-f-week-header" style="margin-top:48px;">Week 4</p>
      <h3 class="apn-f-week-title">Measure the Correlation: Focus Quality vs. RPE</h3>

      <p class="apn-f-body">Week 4 is measurement and optimization. You have 21 days of data. Use it to answer the question this protocol was designed to answer: is your focus quality improving independent of physical fatigue?</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 1: Correlation analysis.</strong> Take your 21 days of session logs. For each session, you have RPE (physical effort) and focus quality (cognitive output). Plot or compare them. The target outcome: focus quality should no longer decline proportionally with RPE. High-RPE sessions in Week 4 should still produce high focus quality in the second half. If that correlation has separated, the protocol is working. If focus quality still tracks directly with RPE, the mitochondrial support or the adenosine management needs further attention.</p>

      <p class="apn-f-body"><strong>Action 2: Technique error review.</strong> Compare technique notes from Week 1 sessions to Week 4 sessions at matched RPE levels. Are you making fewer errors under equivalent physical fatigue? This is the acetylcholine and attention quality metric. Skill acquisition encodes better when acetylcholine is available and attention is sustained. You should see fewer technique breakdowns at the same load level.</p>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="rookie" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Rookie: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Compare your Week 4 average focus quality score to your Week 1 baseline. That number is the gap you closed. Write it down. Rate how consistent the pre-training ritual felt by Day 30. If it feels automatic, it is encoded. That is the foundation for Month 2. Keep it.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="competitor" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Competitor: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full comparison: average focus quality (first vs. second half) Week 4 vs. Week 1. RPE-to-focus correlation. Caffeine timing compliance. Supplement consistency. Identify the one variable with the most room remaining. That is your Month 2 priority. The others can hold.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Athlete: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full correlation analysis. If RPE-to-focus correlation has separated (focus stays high even when RPE is high), the protocol is working. If the correlation is still tight, the Omega-3 DHA support in Module 5 may be the missing variable. Synaptic membrane integrity is a 6 to 8 week adaptation. If you started Omega-3 in Week 2, you are beginning to see the effect now.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Elite: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Full data review. Specifically: when in the session does your cognitive peak now occur compared to Week 1? If the peak window has shifted later into the session, the mitochondrial support is working. Your goal is to push the cognitive peak window into the highest-complexity work of the session. Adjust stack timing in Week 5 to optimize that alignment.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion" style="margin:24px 0;">
        <div style="background:#FFFFFF;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;padding:18px 22px;border-radius:4px;">
          <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Champion: Week 4 Focus</p>
          <p class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;">Architecture review. Pre-training ritual: automatic. Caffeine timing: disciplined. Stack: consistent and timed. Week 4 is confirmation. If all three pillars held for 30 days, you have built the focus system for the next competitive block. Protect it. Do not change it because you feel good. Feeling good is the protocol working.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-f-assignment">
        <p class="apn-f-assignment-label">Your Assignment</p>
        <p>Day 30 measurements: Average focus quality Week 4 vs. Week 1 baseline. First-half vs. second-half focus gap. RPE-to-focus correlation (tighter or looser than Day 1). Supplement compliance rate for Weeks 3 and 4. Retake the Performance Quiz at the link in Module 7 and compare your focus pillar score to your starting score.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ====================================================
       MODULE 5: THE STACK
  ===================================================== -->
  <div id="apn-f-m5" style="background:#FFFFFF;">
    <div class="apn-f-content">
      <p class="apn-f-section-label">The Stack</p>
      <h2 class="apn-f-headline">What Actually Moves the Needle for Focus</h2>
      <div class="apn-f-divider"></div>

      <p class="apn-f-body">Supplements are the final variable in a closed system. The protocol in Module 4 is the foundation. The stack amplifies what the behavioral work already built.</p>

      <!-- PRIMARY: Clarity -->
      <div class="apn-f-product-card">
        <p class="apn-f-product-name">Primary Supplement</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-title">Clarity — Methylene Blue Drops</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-price">$29.99 | Mental Focus Support</p>

        <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">The Mechanism</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-detail">Methylene blue is a synthetic compound that functions as an electron carrier in the mitochondrial electron transport chain. Specifically, it accepts electrons from NADH (at Complex I) and shuttles them directly to cytochrome c (at Complex III), bypassing the standard Complex I-II-III chain. In neural mitochondria that have developed inefficiencies at Complex I or II (which occurs progressively with age, stress, and high cognitive load), methylene blue restores ATP production by providing an alternative electron route. The result is increased mitochondrial efficiency in brain cells, improved ATP availability for synaptic transmission, and reduced reactive oxygen species (ROS) generation from electron chain inefficiency. This is cognitive energy production at the cellular level.</p>

        <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Dose and Timing</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-detail">5 to 10 drops sublingually, 30 to 45 minutes before training. Sublingual delivery bypasses first-pass hepatic metabolism and produces a faster and more complete absorption than oral ingestion. Start at 5 drops for 5 sessions before increasing to 10. The effect is dose-dependent up to approximately 1 mg/kg body weight. Note: methylene blue temporarily stains the mouth blue for 20 to 30 minutes post-administration. This is normal and is not a side effect to manage.</p>

        <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Synergy</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-detail">Clarity addresses the energy substrate for focus (mitochondrial ATP). Ignite addresses the adenosinergic system (caffeine blocking fatigue signal) and the dopaminergic tone (L-theanine modulating the GABA system to prevent anxiety). They work on different mechanisms and can be used together. Do not take them simultaneously. Space Clarity at T-45 and Ignite at T-25 to prevent overlap of peak concentration windows.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- SECONDARY: Ignite (all tiers) -->
      <div class="apn-f-product-card">
        <p class="apn-f-product-name">Secondary Supplement</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-title">Ignite — Energy Powder</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-price">$39.99 | Pre-Training Energy and Focus</p>

        <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">The Mechanism</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-detail">Ignite delivers 150mg natural caffeine plus L-theanine. These two compounds work through different but complementary mechanisms. Caffeine blocks adenosine A1 and A2A receptors in the brain, preventing the fatigue signal from reaching threshold and maintaining alertness. It also increases dopamine receptor sensitivity, amplifying the dopaminergic drive for physical and cognitive performance. L-theanine modulates GABA-A receptors, increasing inhibitory tone in the amygdala and anterior cingulate cortex without sedation. This prevents the anxiety component of caffeine stimulation while preserving the alertness and attentional components. The combination produces sustained, clean focus without the jitteriness or anxiety that caffeine alone at the same dose produces.</p>

        <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Dose and Timing</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-detail">1 scoop mixed in 12 to 16oz water, 20 to 30 minutes before training. Not 5 minutes before. The caffeine absorption curve peaks at 30 to 45 minutes post-ingestion. Taking it 20 minutes before training means the peak concentration aligns with the first 20 to 30 minutes of the session, when technique quality and focus depth matter most. The L-theanine effect begins within 15 minutes and sustains for 3 to 5 hours.</p>

        <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Synergy</p>
        <p class="apn-f-product-detail">Ignite pairs directly with Clarity. Clarity improves the mitochondrial energy production in neural tissue. Ignite optimizes the adenosinergic and dopaminergic signaling on top of that improved energy substrate. Mitochondrial output is the ceiling. The caffeine-theanine system determines how efficiently you operate within that ceiling.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- SUPPORTING: Omega-3 (Athlete, Elite, Champion) -->
      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="athlete">
        <div class="apn-f-product-card">
          <p class="apn-f-product-name">Supporting Supplement</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-title">Omega-3</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-price">$24.99 | Cognitive Performance Support</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">The Mechanism</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">DHA (docosahexaenoic acid) is the primary structural fatty acid in neuronal membranes, constituting approximately 30 to 35% of synaptic membrane phospholipid content. Membrane DHA content directly affects synaptic fluidity, which governs how efficiently neurotransmitter release and receptor binding occur. Low DHA means stiffer synaptic membranes, slower neurotransmitter cycling, and reduced efficiency of acetylcholine-dependent working memory and skill acquisition. Higher DHA is associated with better cognitive performance on working memory tasks and faster skill acquisition rates in research studies. DHA also serves as a precursor to neuroprotectin D1, a resolvin that reduces neuroinflammation, which accumulates with chronic high cognitive load.</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Dose and Timing</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">2g DHA daily. Take with a fat-containing meal. DHA is fat-soluble. Absorption without dietary fat is significantly reduced. Morning with breakfast is the most consistent timing for most athletes. DHA incorporation into neuronal membranes is a 6 to 12 week adaptation process. Start this week and measure cognitive performance at Day 30 and again at Day 60. The 60-day measurement will show more effect than the 30-day.</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Synergy</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">DHA improves the structural substrate of synaptic membranes that acetylcholine and dopamine signaling depend on. Clarity provides energy. Ignite modulates the signaling environment. Omega-3 optimizes the physical structure of the hardware those signals run through. Each layer operates at a different level of the system.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="elite">
        <div class="apn-f-product-card">
          <p class="apn-f-product-name">Supporting Supplement</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-title">Omega-3</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-price">$24.99 | Cognitive Performance Support</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">The Mechanism</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">DHA constitutes 30 to 35% of synaptic membrane phospholipid content. Membrane DHA content governs synaptic fluidity, neurotransmitter release efficiency, and receptor binding speed. At the Elite tier, DHA optimization represents a structural improvement to the cognitive hardware itself. You are not just managing the neurotransmitter signals. You are improving the efficiency of the membrane those signals depend on.</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Dose and Timing</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">2 to 3g DHA daily. With food. Morning preferred for consistency. The 6 to 8 week adaptation window means the Day 60 measurement matters more than Day 30 for this specific supplement. Track it accordingly.</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Synergy</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">Full stack at the Elite tier: Clarity (mitochondrial efficiency), Ignite (adenosinergic and dopaminergic optimization), Omega-3 (synaptic membrane structural integrity). Three different levels of the cognitive performance system addressed simultaneously. Timing is what separates adequate use from precision use at this tier.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-tier-f-block" data-tier="champion">
        <div class="apn-f-product-card">
          <p class="apn-f-product-name">Supporting Supplement</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-title">Omega-3</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-price">$24.99 | Cognitive Performance Support</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">The Mechanism</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">At the Champion tier, DHA is a maintenance and protection tool. Synaptic membrane DHA content declines with age and with chronic neuroinflammation from high training loads. Consistent DHA supplementation maintains the structural quality of neuronal membranes across a competitive career. This is cognitive longevity, not just acute performance.</p>

          <p class="apn-f-product-detail-label">Dose and Timing</p>
          <p class="apn-f-product-detail">2 to 3g DHA daily. Non-negotiable. Every day. The protective effect accumulates over months and years. This is not a supplement you cycle. It is part of the structural maintenance protocol.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="apn-f-warning">
        <p class="apn-f-warning-label">Common Stack Mistake</p>
        <p>Stacking Clarity and Ignite at the same time. Both require sublingual or oral processing windows. Taking them simultaneously compresses their absorption curves and blunts the timing precision that makes the stack effective. Clarity at T-45. Ignite at T-25. The separation is the mechanism. Do not collapse it for convenience.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Gap2 callout if present -->
      <div id="apn-f-gap2-callout" style="display:none;background:#F4F4F2;border:1px solid #E2E8F0;border-left:4px solid #06A5C5;padding:20px 24px;border-radius:4px;margin:32px 0;">
        <p style="font-family:'Barlow',sans-serif;font-size:10px;font-weight:700;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:3px;color:#06A5C5;margin:0 0 8px;">Your Secondary Gap</p>
        <p id="apn-f-gap2-text" class="apn-f-body" style="margin:0;"></p>
